{{Infobox tennis biography |AustralianOpenDoublesresult = |FrenchOpenDoublesresult = |AustralianOpenresult = 1R ([[2007 Australian Open – Men's Singles|2007]]) |FrenchOpenresult = 1R ([[2006 French Open – Men's Singles|2006]], [[2007 French Open – Men's Singles|2007]]) |WimbledonDoublesresult = 2R ([[2006 Wimbledon Championships – Men's Doubles|2006]]) |Wimbledonresult = 2R ([[2005 Wimbledon Championships – Men's Singles|2005]]) |USOpenDoublesresult = |USOpenresult = 2R ([[2006 US Open – Men's Singles|2006]]) |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|08|09|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], Italy |careerprizemoney = [[United States dollar|US$]]812,621 |country = {{ITA}} |doublesrecord = 1–14 |doublestitles = 0 |height = {{height|m=1.85}} |highestdoublesranking = No. 136 (30 January 2012) |plays = Left-handed |residence = Syracuse, Italy |singlesrecord = 17–36 |singlestitles = 0 |highestsinglesranking = No. 68 (26 February 2007) |turnedpro = 1998 |retired = 2014 }}
'''Alessio di Mauro''' (born 9 August 1977) is a former professional tennis player from Italy. During his career, he reached the final of one ATP tournament, the [[2007 ATP Buenos Aires]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Eric Weil|title=Monaco Beats Di Mauro for ATP Title|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/25/AR2007022500658.html|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=25 February 2007}}</ref> On 26 February 2007 the left-hander reached his career high ranking of world no. 68.
==Betting scandal== On 10 November 2007, at a position of world no. 124, di Mauro was the first player to be sanctioned after being embroiled in a betting scandal. Di Mauro received a [[$]]60,000 ([[£]]29,000) fine and 9 months banning from the [[ATP Tour]] for an offense that carried a maximum punishment of three years. Some officials called for a harsher punishment. However, di Mauro was not betting on the outcome of his own matches nor did he attempt to influence the outcomes of matches. He was found to be betting from 2 November 2006 to 12 June 12, 2007, and was caught as a result of an investigation beginning in April 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Clive White|title=Alessio di Mauro banned by ATP|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/atptour/2325479/Alessio-di-Mauro-banned-by-ATP.html|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=11 November 2007}}</ref>
